1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:06,000
It's 3am. Something's broken.
You want an AI agent to triage it.

2
00:00:06,500 --> 00:00:12,000
But would you let one loose on your production systems?

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Leavitt reads your dashboards the way an on-call engineer does.

4
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:26,500
Metrics, logs, client load, what just deployed.
It correlates them and tells you what broke.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,000
And it physically cannot touch the thing it's watching.

6
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:38,000
It's a state machine. Every step is checked against the graph before it runs.

7
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:43,500
And the graph only knows how to read.
Diagnosis with no off-switch to flip.

8
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Here it is on a real incident.

9
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:58,000
It finds the failing service, names the flag that caused it,
traces the cascade through frontend and checkout, and backs it all with evidence.

10
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:05,000
It runs headless. Nemotron on Crusoe drives it through the Hermes harness.

11
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:13,000
The model layer routes through TrueFoundry's gateway,
so when a provider browns out, the investigation fails over and keeps going.

12
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:21,000
Wire it to your alerts and this is what a shift looks like.

13
00:01:21,500 --> 00:01:27,000
Webhook in, agent runs, report out.
Every step on the record.

14
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:31,000
Twenty-five runs a day, zero confident-wrong.

15
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Here is what happens when the data lies.
Kill a source, feed it garbage.

16
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:42,500
A bare agent gets confident and wrong.

17
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Leavitt degrades, or says inconclusive,
and it never once invents a cause it can't support.

18
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Every investigation is on the record. Nothing it did is a mystery.

19
00:01:56,500 --> 00:01:59,500
It only reads, so you can point it at production and walk away.

20
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Leave it to Leavitt.
